<HEADLINE>
<P>
WARNER RIDGE 'EYESORE' 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Your article (April 23) regarding the "Warner Ridge Debate" leads me to applaud 
this paper and all media in general for exposing the corruption that exists in 
government and elsewhere. It amazes me that Joy Picus would state such a 
bold-face lie that the lawsuit is "about developers who didn't get everything 
they wanted through the city's planning process, the same fair and open process 
that everybody else has to go through." 
</P>
<P>
This "shoot from the hip" comment is the best example of the half-truths that 
one has come to expect from Picus during her years in office. The fact is that 
Spound Co. and Johnson Wax have earned approvals from every city and state 
agency during the five years of public hearings, since the inception of the 
project. This includes the city Planning Commission, the Citizens Advisory 
Committee, and so on. 
</P>
<P>
This project was disapproved at the City Council level without any background 
evidence, ignoring the recommendations of their experts such as city planners, 
engineers, attorneys, as well as a good percentage of the general public who 
live in the area and who supported the project after years of attending public 
hearings and listening to the proposals put forward by the developers. 
</P>
<P>
Now the taxpayers must pay for this by the lost dollars in property and 
licensing taxes, as well as the cost of defending a $100-million lawsuit and 
the exposure of a $100-million-plus judgment which they will ultimately have to 
pay. 
</P>
<P>
This valuable, undeveloped piece of land will remain an eyesore as long as our 
politicians oppose worthwhile projects purely for political reasons and do not 
act in the best interest of the public. 
</P>
<P>
WILLIAM J. ZUMWALT 
</P>
<P>
Encino 
</P>
</TEXT>
