<DATE>
<P>
April 30, 1990, Monday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Business; Part D; Page 2; Column 1; Financial Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
109 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
BRIEFLY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Machine Tool Orders Jump: Machine tool orders surged 36.6% in March, to $265.85 
million from $194.55 million in February, the Assn. for Manufacturing 
Technology said in a report. 
</P>
<P>
However, compared to March, 1989, last month's machine tool orders, which are 
highly cyclical in nature, were down 8.5%. Year-to-date machine tool orders 
stood at $661.70 million, down 17.6% from the 1989 figure of $803.30 million. 
Industry analysts attributed the overall decrease in orders to a reduced demand 
from the automobile sector. March orders for domestic machine tools increased 
20.6% over February, while orders for foreign machine tools jumped 104%. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
